## Mathematical content

- An elementary conjunction is a finite conjunction of literals.
- A minterm relative to a finite variable list `P_1,\ldots,P_n` is an elementary conjunction containing exactly one of `P_i` or `\neg P_i` for each `i`.
- A formula is in disjunctive normal form if it is a finite disjunction of elementary conjunctions.
- The existence theorem states: for every `\varphi\in\WFF`, there exists a formula `\psi\in\WFF` in disjunctive normal form such that `\varphi\equiv\psi`.
- The satisfiability criterion states: a DNF formula is satisfiable exactly when at least one of its conjunction terms contains no complementary pair of literals.

